Conflicts between ruling and opposition parties in S. Korea
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, January 28 (KCNA) -- The opposition "Grand National Party" of South Korea expanded its struggle out of the "National Assembly," according to news reports from Seoul. 
   It had fought against arbitrary acts of the ruling parties at the "assembly."&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   On January 24, it held a rally in Masan, South Kyongsang Province, to denounce the Kim Dae Jung regime's failed state policy and illegal inspection. It bitterly lashed out at  crimes of the "people's government," taking issue with political inspections by  the "Agency for National Security Planning" exposed through the office room No. 529 of the "assembly", railroading of bills by the ruling parties through the "assembly" in the absence of opposition, increase of unemployment and  economic bankruptcy.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   After the rally, members of the opposition party waged a street demonstration urging the apology of the present chief executive.
   The ruling parties, the "National Congress for New Politics" (NCNP) and the "United Liberal Democrats" are setting themselves against the resistance of the opposition party. The "NCNP" is trying to destroy the foundation of the opposition party.
